                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman N</hi> 58). Hatcher gave me the parcel now produced—I took Debenham in custody. <hi rend="italic">Debenham called</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18501021-name-532" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18501021-name-532" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501021-name-532" type="surname" value="BEDOE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501021-name-532" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE BEDOE</persName>
                  </hi>. This parcel seems to be what is called <hi rend="italic">seconds</hi>—I have not known you dress anything of the kind for a long time.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Has Mr. Smith any such on his premises? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It is very likely he has—it is a very common bristle, most masters have them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18501021-name-533" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18501021-name-533" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501021-name-533" type="surname" value="TURPIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18501021-name-533" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE TURPIN</persName>
                  </hi>. I should think these are what we call <hi rend="italic">seconds</hi>—it is six weeks or two months since you had anything of the sort.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Are there such on the premises? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I do not know that they could be got at without any one seeing them taken; some of the shopmen would see—they are kept in the shop, which is away from the workshop.</p>
